<Layout title="Pluto's Demotion" description="Why the IAU reclassified Pluto as a dwarf planet in 2006.">
  <h1>From Planet to Dwarf Planet</h1>
  <p>
    On 24 August 2006, at a meeting in Prague, the International Astronomical
    Union (IAU) voted to adopt a formal definition of the word "planet" for the
    first time. Under the new definition, Pluto no longer qualified.
  </p>

  <h2>The three rules of being a planet</h2>
  <p>The IAU decided that, to be a planet, a body in the Solar System must:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>orbit the Sun;</li>
    <li>be massive enough for its own gravity to pull it into a round shape;</li>
    <li>have "cleared the neighbourhood" around its orbit of other objects.</li>
  </ol>

  <!-- Positive tabindex disrupts focus order (tabindex) -->
  <div class="callout" tabindex="5">
    Pluto meets the first two rules, but <strong>not the third</strong>. It
    shares the crowded Kuiper Belt with countless other icy bodies, so it has not
    "cleared its neighbourhood." Bodies that meet rules 1 and 2 but not 3 are
    called <em>dwarf planets</em>.
  </div>

  <!-- Image deliberately missing alt -->
  <figure>
    <img src="/images/charon-true-color.jpg" width="360" class="content-img" />
    <figcaption>
      Charon, Pluto's largest moon — so big that some argue Pluto-Charon is a
      "double dwarf planet."
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>A controversial vote</h2>
  <!-- Low-contrast pull quote (color-contrast) -->
  <blockquote class="muted-fail">
    "Eight planets and a swarm of dwarf planets — that's a Solar System I can
    live with." Not everyone agreed. The vote was contested, and many
    researchers and members of the public still argue Pluto deserves planet
    status today.
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    Today Pluto is the best-known of five officially recognised dwarf planets,
    alongside Ceres, Haumea, Makemake, and Eris. Learn about
    <a href="/orbit">what makes Pluto's orbit so unusual</a>.
  </p>
</Layout>
